    <p class="firstpara">This page describes the ATF mechanism for
    linking a scholarly commentary to its base text.</p>

<esp:h>Commentary Protocol</esp:h>

<p>ATF commentaries do not need a special protocol: four field designations are always available for dividing commentary lines into different parts:</p>

<dl>
<dt><code class="cookbook">!qt</code></dt>    <dd>to introduce a quote from the base text;</dd>
<dt><code class="cookbook">!bs</code></dt>    <dd>to introduce the base word(s) commented upon;</dd>
<dt><code class="cookbook">!cm</code></dt>    <dd>to introduce a commentary on the base word(s);</dd>
<dt><code class="cookbook">!zz</code></dt>    <dd>to mark text as not belonging to a quote, base of comment.</dd>
</dl>
<p>each of these elements must be surrounded by white space: instead of <code>[!cm</code> write <code>!cm [</code>.</p>

<!--<p>The milestone <code>,b</code> may be followed by a number, so that
each <code>,b</code> field designation within a single line of text has a unique identifier. The base text may then be identified in a comment line as follows:</p>

<pre class="example">#,b1 = SB Anzu 1 = cams/anzu:Q002769 56
#,b2 = CT 19, pl.44, K 04226 = dcclt:P365422 o i 11</pre>

<p>At the moment those notes don't do anything - but at some point in the future it may be possible to transform those into actual links. If the text referred to is not available anywhere on oracc (doesn't have a project name), and/or doesn't have a Q or P number, you may write those notes more informally - but obviously they will not result in a link.</p>

<esp:h>Example</esp:h>

<p>This example is based on a real-life text but has been adapted to
showcase all three field designations.</p>

<pre class="example">
&amp;P415763 = CM 31, 139

#project: cams/gkab
#atf: use unicode
#atf: use commentary
#atf: lang akk-x-stdbab

@tablet
@obverse

1. ,b BE iz-bu SAG.DU UR.MAH GAR NUN LUGAL{+tu₂} ŠU₂{+tu₂} DAB{+bat}
#,b = SB Šumma Izbu 8 = cams/gkab:Q003013 1

2. ,b1 meṭ-lu-tu₂ DU{+ak} ,o me₂-eṭ-lu-tu₂ : ,b2 ši-bu-u₂-tu₂ : MIN
